No liberating amendments to Tymoshenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian Parliament today rejected the request to abolish the paragraphs on the basis of which the opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko was sentenced in the context of a revision of the Criminal Code.
The new regime, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned ex-Prime Ministers, was rejected by the Members at the second reading of the motion for a reduction in the penalties for economic offences.
Timoshenko had been sentenced to seven years in prison in October because of the conclusion of an alleged adverse agreement with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet valid, and in December the appeal of the convicted to the court is to be dealt with.
Timoshenko himself calls the sentence the political revenge of the regime and also in the West the trial made the suspicions of the bias of the court arise.
The request to remove paragraph 365, on the basis of which the Ex-Prime Minister was sentenced from the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 Members.
226 votes would have been necessary for its adoption.
