The menu of a fat child: It does not breakfast and eats for dinner sausage
More than a third of the children from 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, with 9% of all students and 5% of all children overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that adipose children usually come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle.
So it turns out once again how important for the healthy development of a human being is the environment in which he grows up and are the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more often on the table than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of the overweight children had an evening meal on the day before the education campaign under the motto "Adipositas is No Accident".
In families with Dickerchen, sport is not just one of the favourite jobs, however, the majority of today's students - only 15 percent replied that their parents find themselves at least once a week for active exercise.
Survey of children under 900
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, with almost 900 children from primary schools being interviewed throughout the Czech Republic.
This was already the second year of the action "Adipositas is not a coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Insurance and the Unilever Society.
Up to now, more than 12 thousand pupils from 4 and 8 classes participated in the project.
Unhealthy food and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the frightening increase in the number of children with overweight or even obesity.
"Only half of the children surveyed said, for example, five times a day to eat breakfast-second breakfast lunch-vesper evening bread - one of the main conditions for healthy eating," that is one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that relative small things, such as the family's regular breakfast time, are also important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 per cent of the pupils' families.
And - in most families everyone breakfasts alone.
The worst finding was that every tenth family does not have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is regarded as the cornerstone of healthy daily diet.
The survey showed, among other things, that the families of overweight children consume much more unhealthy apples.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet limonades every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 per cent of the children surveyed are engaged in sports, only less than half of their parents do so - that is, only 15 per cent.
Set your own menu
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (104 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own menus based on their appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children prefer between 12 and 15 in terms of diet is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among her favorite dishes were many flour, meat dishes and, of course, sweets.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet limonads", is emphasized in the final report on this survey.
At lunchtime, i.e. the main court, pasta won just before poultry.
The children almost did not like legumes and also the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Return to Health
At the same time, however, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits when they get the right information.
"The survey participants' control group, which completed the questionnaire following the conclusion of the explanatory lecture "Adipositas is not a coincidence", has in many cases been subject to a marked shift in preferences towards principles of healthy nutrition", is mentioned in the project results.
This was obvious, for example, in the sweet Limos, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
The children also crossed many poultry or fish as the main dish of the day in the questionnaire and were ready to eat less noodles or sweet food.
