V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The originally careless ride becomes due to a series of completely avoidable, dilettant mistakes to the routine journey to the early layer.
Although it was possible to fulfil the ambitions to a large extent, what is the point of doing so already if no one obviously wanted to do a little more?
Even before he came to the counter, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
He promised to move the already old game series "Need for speed" back to a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples he didn't seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about the adapted passages in which the main protagonist rises out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you're already used to it at NFS, in the end it's a lot different than you expected.
Certainly - potentially it is quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is reduced by some unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So there are no mistakes anymore, but rather signs of the basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure begins very well.
For the first time, the story is introduced, whose main character Jack has certain problems of a personal character; the only solution seems to be to take part in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, that is, on the west coast, you're on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea includes a whole series of interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is played on another track and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
One has no moment the impression that game would always offer the same.
Some environments are still very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphic does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But the drive through the desert, through autumn landscape or up through deep snowy landscape seems visually very pleasant.
Sometimes untypical elements bring a little variety into the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts vision.
In the mountains, in turn, you have to make sure that you are not thrown away by a avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are quite well built.
Only a few, but they're enough.
For a while you try to overtake the required number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time (classical race against the stopwatch), then you expect a personal duel with a single opponent.
And that's what the police are going to do. They want to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
This is more about some interactive animations in which Jack flees from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
However, it is surprising that in the game there are far fewer such passages than one would expect (in concrete terms only three).
In the end, this is more of an advantage, because at least this element has no chance of getting bored - it belongs in the context of the above mentioned elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model walks in the footsteps of the previous parts.
This means that, from today's point of view, it does not rip out trees, on the other hand, one could not claim it would be bad.
Anyone looking for realistic simulations needs to look elsewhere.
But the local driving model is still very well suited for an action-loaded race, although the competition could be improved.
Until then, everything is in order.
Real problems arise only after some time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not quite OK.
From a game of this kind it is hardly to be expected that it computes complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have practically no impact on any object knowing how the car behaves, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: When passing through or passing on opposite cars, the other cars are "tipped" in some places only easily, but in others, almost identical situation, you get into the slip and turn wild pirouettes.
Or take the cart to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn't matter any more, it's annoying all the time.
The restarts are solved in such a way: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then the game throws you back to the last point of the track.
Only - in each race you only have five restarts.
If you've exhausted it, it's all starting from the front.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in the case that something doesn't work, but you shouldn't rely on it.
Sometimes, however, not even the restart helps, since nothing else helps to learn from the critical section of the head.
It is extremely unpleasant that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some curves, for example, need to be run through in a very specific way, or you simply don't fit through.
Where you meet "civil" cars at the appropriate point, you always have the same configuration, no matter if you come first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations when you see that the opponent passes in front of one playing on two approaching cars, but until you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to bypass or brake them.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is designed in such a way that it always gets close to your nose to this situation.
The opponents have further advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent and again here without regard for the timing.
At the craziest, this is at the conclusion of the game on the long bridge, which you pass in opposite direction.
The opponent must overtake one of us here, apparently, to the devil.
And if he's already in front of you, he'll take a look at you, of course, so you start driving your own car in Klump a few times.
Of course - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting but this intention is so clear that it avoids the joy of the game quickly.
And that's a shame, because despite a simple driving model, the game is quite entertaining and, in some cases, it's also so loaded that you almost don't know where one's head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what it is - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that can't get bored, or something else...
An unusual idea is also the change of cars during the races.
You must not miss the filling stations on the track, because right here you can change the car, although in most cases the car that you have right now is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight motorways and exotic super sports cars for the technical rides, for example on the Serpentine in the mountain.
Hand in hand with the mode of game history also goes the task mode (requests) - i.e. the races in the individual locations you know from history.
Here there are not only medals, but also points of experience to gain for one's own profile, which is common to the tasks (requests) and history.
In order to get to the higher level of driver, various objects have to be unlocked: starting from the car, up to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is combined with the online Autolog feature, which compares its own results with other players and also provides for other collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible carvings is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you come by car to a subway tunnel (meinetwegen) where you rest on the rails in the dark (meinetwegen).
On the tacho you can see numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (menet roads), but there is one single metro coming from the back and driving an uncompromised to scrap.
In our editorial, we will probably argue for a long time about whether that was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases quite appealing and even brilliant here and there.
It is all the more annoying that at some exciting moments the frequency of repeat images becomes slower and sometimes quite dramatic.
However, this applies in particular to accidents involving a larger number of stakeholders, where a continuous FPS does not benefit at all.
The sound reproduction is as far as OK and the soundtrack is taste.
In an effort to address as wide a scale as possible rather young audiences, a soundtrack a lá "everything" was created - but who buys such a game already because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are more mixed.
If the game would not be damaged by the mentioned totally unnecessary mistakes, we could have argued with the chest tone that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's how the game seems kind of unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but one should be prepared to look at those mistakes with the power of airport lights.
Concert of the "Students of the Same Revolution" with singing ensembles of Karlsuniversität
The Festa Academica festival now offers for the third time the addition of the World Student Day with the anniversary of the Samten Revolution and its musical experience.
In the course of the festival, the twenty professional choirs and university choirs are presented.
The festival focuses on the two concerts that will take place on 17 November.
"The Karlsuniversität has a large part to play in the festival."
"The choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Human Studies is also represented among the participants and the festival committee is also attended by Rector Václav Hampl," led by the head of the organizing team Jakub Čaloun.
The absolute highlight of the festival is the public concert of specialist choirs, which takes place on 17 November from 2 p.m. on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program features the composition of the important Czech jazzist Karel R theička "Celebration Jazz Mass".
In the evening hours, the concert "Students of the velvet revolution" (Studenty Sametu) takes place in the gala rooms of the Volkshaus in Vinohrady, where the choir also occurs, choirs of Karlsuniversität are not excluded.
Festa Academica sets the goal not only to celebrate the World Student Day and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Samten Revolution, but to present choral music to the public at the highest level and to promote the creative cooperation of young people.
The main organiser is the association of Czech choirs in cooperation with the Johannes-Kepler-Gymnasium.
Bohuslav Svoboda, the mayor of the capital Prague and Václav Hampl, the rector of Karlsuniversität, took over the patronage of the entire event.
The festival takes place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and in Pardubice.
In addition to concerts, the schedule includes numerous music meetings, student-happanings, matinees and other events.
Detailed information can be found on the website of the festival www.festacademica.cz
