This was also the basis of Watsen's thoroughly prepared corporate culture.
"For us from IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and was also successful for a whole century because it remained faithful to its principles and did not hesitate to change everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technologies, business and society over the course of our first century.
We hope that we will do even more in the next hundred years," said Samuel J. Palmisano, today's director of the company on the occasion of the anniversary.
A thoughtful system
In the 1930s, Watson had already taken social care of his employees - in a similar way as the Ba the entrepreneur in Czechoslovakia: the IBM people had paid as one of the first American employees, insurance by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as work clothing and a thoughtful remuneration system for the best newcomers and dealers.
