IBM History: From cheese cutter to all-world flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines) founded a hundred years ago in New York had initially a rather complicated name - Computing Tablating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was taken over only in 1924 - originally it was a trademark name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the future company IBM laid the foundation for the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They had technologies such as the famous card clocks to register the beginning and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint was the architect of this new company, who also chaired the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This leader then even put IBM's founders in the shadow - on Watson's ideas is still based on the company's invincible culture and identity.
Watson headed the company until 1952.
IBM, as already revealed by the name, began with the production and distribution of all possible machines for the trade - from sausage and cheese cutters, to cashing.
In the first four decades in which Watson headed the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he was in the chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM of NASA helped lead flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous human flight to the moon.
In 1964 IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which determined the computer standard of that time, came onto the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand it bought the consultant part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and entered the business with high value-added consulting services and services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the concept of "Smart Planet".
It expresses the intention to use technologies in a wise way in areas not even planned so far, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and urban administration.
In the commercial sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smart Commerce" platform, which aims to help traders to lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
Already in 1932 IBM founded a branch in Czechoslovakia at that time - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today IBM ČR also operates, among other things, a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central Office for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and here is also a top world-level research team that deals with voice recognition technology.
