Developments in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five state travel agencies in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sports Tourist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies mainly sold only trips to the socialist Eastern bloc countries at the time, and only chosen ones were allowed to travel to the West at the time.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period 1962-72, when it was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even citizens of the Eastern bloc (also the Czechoslovakians) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Already at that time the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or even stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
This was not the case for a long time.
The so-called foreign exchange practice - the condition for an exit to the West - was only given "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that continues to this day.
The Saturday revolution of 1989 followed a journey revolution of the Czechs on foot.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays last year in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which one is no longer aware of today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989 at all, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, foreign exchange obligations were abolished in the neighbouring Western European countries, which led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their journeys to the West for a long time, everyone wanted at least a few days to be there.
The Czech holidaymakers slept in the park when travelling to Paris in the tent, because at that time, who would have had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a guest house.
A typical feature of travel abroad by Czechs was then a packed trunk with canned food, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and thus the average wages also increased, which led to a further important moment in 1997.
Thanks to increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to prepare regular trips through charter flights after 1997, which, thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantity discounts, made flight travel incredibly cheaper compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already had currencyless payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-general" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand of the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was made - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying to far distant sunny countries each year; twelve exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
The 100 Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another important moment in the era that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the USA lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which definitely included our country among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacation abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 CZK per capita for a single vacation including the cost of the resort.
