After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
That's easy - you only have to log in to Facebook.
"We found that it was not difficult to come to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the main author of a recent report by the UK Ideas Factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook's hiding of personal data is so encyclopaedic, Bartlett says that researchers simply have to use the advertising tool of the site to precisely define their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of extreme right-wing groups across Europe and then targeted them with add-ons, but instead of linking themselves to a new band or diet product, the add-ons invited users to a survey asking about their educational status, their attitude to violence, and their assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 followers of 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries - without having to leave their office once.
"It's quite a new research method," Bartlett says.
Some of the results hardly surprise. Online promoters of extreme right groups are mostly young, male and angry about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those behind their computer screens."
DEMO's work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in scientists' hands.
Ideas factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything, from health issues to societal trends such as in "likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users, who add on average three content per day, Facebook's "Data Supernova" generates a research boom that increased the number of scientific works with the name of this site in title by nearly 800% over the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study people through this page, which you usually do not reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you used to try to question people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"They had to inform the party first and it would never have granted them access," Bartlett says.
"With Facebook it all falls away - you go straight to them."
Others say that the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno from the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their full-blown noise on Facebook are significantly more inclined to drown than students who were silent about this topic.
Moreno suggests that equal-ranking students, such as residential consultants, monitor the page and help a student when they post too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you haven't recognized it," said Dimitri Christakis, Morenos co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, Washington Post.
