Stories about foaming in school and at college are widespread.
There were incidents in which teachers gave their students the examination answers so that they could do well in their performance checks themselves.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and foams are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
As studies prove, we lie every day between 10 and 200 times.
Many of these lies, however, are regarded as emergency lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Identifying lies or "discovering lies" is one important thing to learn for every person, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as Scharaden, in which it is the goal to call "Hab yourself!", detaching a deception is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that carried out far-reaching research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths have been exposed to the lie.
Lies look you in the eye.
They stutter, stutter, rot and do not always beat.
However, it cannot be concluded from this that these liars are difficult to reveal and detangle.
A trained liar can penetrate to the truth by learning something about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, questions and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the comprehensive and constantly growing field of detachment. And it is clear that detaching a deception is a modern ability that is easy to learn and helps us to find justice in our complex world, especially if the hiring or questioning of persons or negotiations or administration belongs to one's own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at appreciating other people's interests and controlling their own emotions, and they intuitively feel how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people, that men notice more "self-oriented" lies than women whose lies "focus more on others" - usually they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are usually "fat lies").
We also know that when a person as an evildoer has been disguised, others feel less guilty about lying to that person.
How do you know if anyone's lying?
First, by observing the normal behaviour of this person.
This is called "baselining", the starting position.
It provides a reference point for subsequent evaluation of changes.
Watch the attitude, the smile, the voice quality of your test person.
You should know better when someone usually keeps tripping with the foot, so that they do not wrongly accuse him if he trips with the foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of striking verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Look at these accumulations as alarm bells that scream, not as evidence of a detachment.
People who are mistaken may become stronger when they try to remember their story. Maybe their feet are pointing towards the door or they are leaning towards the exit, changing their position significantly or showing a "distress after the attitude interview", this deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in attitude when all hard questions are over.
Askers often falsely signal that a recruitment interview is over, just to look after this relaxation after the recruitment interview.
Also, pay attention to the language of your test person.
Scott Peterson's runner is famous when he used the past form when he claimed his murdered wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceptive people can also use a dissipating language: "I had no sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question overall.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth ... as far as I am known ... according to the best knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer more perceptive than factual, which often causes the alarm bells to shirk.
There is no magic to detach lies, but you can learn skills that make it possible to detach.
Thanks to these abilities, anyone can become less likely to be the victim of fraud, both in private and in professional life.
