The decline in economic activity up to November has led to a steady increase in unemployment in the Mexican State. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, as from January to March there were 55,053 people in Sinaloas without employment, which represents 4.53% of the labour force. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28% and from July to September to 6.19 percent, which results in 74,000 unemployed in Sinaloa. That is 18,969 more people than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa this year is based on several factors: the economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented, the policy of public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are seeing at the moment is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, the loss of liquidity on the market as a result of cuts in the funds by the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because it is not easy for those who are under ban to let them work for themselves, to invest them or to use something else," he said.
Migration stopped
