On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional complaint filed by the local legislature and judged the State Commissioner's vote on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal", since he did not have the right to "decision or veto against it".
In an interview on the possibility of the individual counting of votes, María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, there was now the possibility that the local electoral authority could partially or completely count the ballot.
Thus, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted The results in the minutes do not agree; the minutes on counting and calculating votes do not appear by act or are not in the possession of the chairman of the election committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the protocols.
Furthermore, if there is a difference between the alleged winner and that who is in second place, which is equal to or less than one percent, the total number of complete ballots may be counted, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request by the party/coalition chairman, who is the second of the above-mentioned candidates.
The vote may also be counted in its entirety if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is found that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that an explicit request is made by a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the electoral packages that were subject to partial counting would be excluded.
