Fujimori returned to the hospital for medical examinations
The former president Alberto Fujimori was delivered to a public hospital on Tuesday to investigate the muscle loss of his legs, informed his home doctor.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is 25 years of imprisonment for violation of human rights during his reign (1990-2000), has several diseases, including tongue cancer, which operates four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a congressman and his personal doctor, told television that Fujimori would be examined for three days in the Peruvian hospital Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower body groups.
Aguinaga commented that, in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but he did not wish to do so because he considered him innocent.
He has been operated on four times on tongue cancer and he has lost 18 kilos of weight. In addition to other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and blood flow problems in the legs, the doctor counted.
Fujimori has been in the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Speciales de la policía detention centre since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squad of the Peruvian army, which was secretly active during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will begin their visit from Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet with his Mexican colleague Felipe Calderón next Wednesday. According to the Uruguayan president, this will be the highlight of his busy schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of both presidents in the city of Guadalajara "suits itself for the exchange of information on all policies between the two countries", announced the South American country's presidential office on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is looking for support for Calderón with regard to the incident with France, when the French head of government Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude those countries which are still tax havens from the international community, which was rejected by Uruguay and prompted a question to his ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has presided over the G20 since November, a group of the most powerful emerging and industrialised countries in the world. Since January this year, there has been an agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation with the South American country.
In recent years, the Uruguayan Government has tried to speed up the implementation of agreements to exchange tax information in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which includes countries that have not introduced all the international standards for tax cooperation.
At business level, there has been a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
