MSS announces a research protocol for finding the gene for obesity
The social insurance institution of Mexico is leading a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, which is supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Institute of Mexico) announced that it is conducting a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth" with which the genetic markers are to be found in association with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Medical Research Department, Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Esspecialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, said that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutrition specialists and social workers was set up.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate course at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and at the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politecnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested people can come to the IMSS sports facilities in the valley of Mexico, where every Saturday tests with children and young people are carried out from 8.00 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation began at the sports field of Cuauhtémoc (west of the state of México) and continued since 8 October at the sports field of Nezahualcóyolt (east of the state of México).
If the target of 500 to 600 subjects is reached, the study will continue on the sports field of Independentencia (in the south of the capital district) and be completed on the one of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He stated that the objective of the study was to identify the factors and the role of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases in Mexican children and adolescents.
On the occasion of the global day of diabetes, he stated that it was hoped that three thousand children and adolescents aged between six and 14 should complete nutrition-related questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They will also be asked questions about their physical activity and their family history of illness in order to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He further stated that on the said Saturdays, subjects would be measured (weight, size, waist size), blood pressure controlled and blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (invitation of genes related to obesity in childhood).
Cruz López stressed that this study would be carried out in the context of the concern of healthcare professionals about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys showed that in almost six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent. Overweight was also dramatically increased," stressed IMSS specialist.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the people of Mexico differed from that of other peoples.
He indicated that a Mexican (e) was an average of 65% Indian-American, 30% European, and 5% African, reflecting the genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity express itself in the inability to burn the excess of the energy (calories) that we have taken, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the study participants would be a comprehensive study of children who would determine whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even examine the occurrence of dark skin folds in the neck and the inner arm (akanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and diabetes at the pre-stage.
All information would be treated confidentially and told the parents in writing by the doctors. The doctors explain all the measurement results to the parents and propose changes in the lifestyle that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz López explained that there would be three basic factors that are responsible for obesity, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of movement, that is, lack of movement in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport, instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, i.e. increased consumption of sugary beverages and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.), together with a high intake of fat and protein, as well as the genetics to be analysed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents blow holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico, UNAM, developed asphalts modified with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs drawn from the road surface were taken into account, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 holes if the rainy season broke out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city of the valley of Mexico), Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warned and assured that if the laying and maintenance of the asphalt surface would be adequate, the number of holes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his talk "technically-based impact holes", which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with an extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the appearance of impact holes.
He explained that asphalt - the most heavy part of the oil - is a hydrocarbons compound, one of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other part a low - the so-called maltene. Together, they give the road surface its characteristic toughelastic behavior.
The teeth-elastic behaviour of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very viscous and at 50°C it is almost firm, while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer explained.
The FQ's researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of a flexible road surface, consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lie a wear layer made of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then fortified.
Every single stone of this wear layer had been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be distributed even better," the chemical engineer said.
