Of the seven lophoscopists in the CTI department, this week Eliazar González had a standby service, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working for 21 years in criminal investigations.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities in Chocó, where he often had to go to the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies he was supposed to identify were located.
In 2000, he moved to Valle and after completing the necessary courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin that is exposed to friction, i.e. the palms and feet.
During the week of deployment against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliaszar was told to pack clothing for at least three days.
Something big was expecting him.
He flew from Palmira to Cauca on Friday night.
He knew that he should identify two bodies and that there was a suspicion that one of the men who had led the oldest guerrilla in the world could be one. Therefore, he should take the ten-finger print sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he reached the place where the body was located by means of the investigation, he could not identify it because of his physical appearance, for this was not least similar to the illustrations he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer in the area, did not wear glasses and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a lupe, ink, a plant shell and a flashlight, Eliasar compared the fingerprints of the body with those on the print sheet.
He had seen it correctly: it was Alfonso Cano.
The same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for telling the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was actually the head of the FARC.
Find Tracks
For a dactyloscope from Sijín in Cali, the assessment given to President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the use of "Cano" was very important.
Many people don't know our work.
Daktyloscopy is an exact science without a rate of error that can be a key factor in the resolution of a crime.
Lophoscopes not only identify bodies, they also support investigations into murder and robbery, and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When they are arrested, many criminals present false identity papers or they have none.
We take them the fingerprints and search them in the database.
The researcher told us that he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house when he was stealing a thief, because the thief had just stood up with his hand at this point when he pulled out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are not suitable for the loss of fingerprints, but in this case we were able to take the full print and identify the criminal who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
Fingerprints can also be used to relieve or burden suspects of murder.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by snuff bottles.
In the investigation it was assumed that a family member might be suspected, and in fact a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, it is linked to the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI dictyloscope said that "the fingerprints would be removed from the object with chemical or physical reagents."
If they appear, a plant shell or a tape will be used to take it.
After that, the prints are sent to Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Personal Status Office.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identity papers," the CTI expert explained.
He said not everything was as it would be shown in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything is gold, which shines, not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a corresponding comparison.
