This committee recommends that the government amend the penal law in such a way as to allow accompanied suicide and euthanasia where this election takes place, in patients who are considered able to make such a decision.
As a starting point, the experts quote a recently published survey of the independent company EIU, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries of the globe.
Although Canada ranked 10, the study notes that "the medical care of death in Canada has produced a culture in which people are afraid to cut the subject of death".
Medical care or not: 77% of Canadians have no access to painkillers, the experts appointed by the Royal Society of Canada tell us.
And despite the majority of Canadians' desire to die at home, however, 68.6% of them finally die in the hospital.
From the country as a whole, the rate is the highest in Quebec with 86% of deaths in the hospital.
In the delicate question of euthanasia and accompanied suicide, the report's authors come to conclusions which are contrary to the position of the federal government, which has already taken on board, not wishing to make any amendments to the penal law concerning euthanasia and accompanied suicide.
However, according to the experts who have inspected all those countries whose approach to euthanasia and accompanied suicide has legalized or decriminalised, there is no evidence that such decriminalisation would lead to the use of euthanasia or accompanied suicide by incompetent or unwilling persons.
On the contrary, there are far more cases of such violations, especially in countries where euthanasia and accompanied suicide are not legalized, as confirmed yesterday by Jocelyn Downie, co-signer of the report, in a teleconference.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Even accompanied suicide is practiced in Canada, although here it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canada’s Support for Euthanasia
Let us consider that according to an Angus-Reid survey conducted in 2010, 85% of Canadians had already benefited from euthanasia, as they feel that these people would at the end of their lives make it possible to alleviate their sufferings.
And 66% believe that the fact that euthanasia is legalized does not lead to the message that the life of elderly or disabled people is of less value.
With regard to the persons who have already practised an accompanying suicide, 41% of respondents feel that they should not be prosecuted.
As far as patient maintenance or discontinuation of resources is concerned, the situation is less clear, according to the report's author.
Similarly, they suggest in their recommended list that the criminal law should specify that the removal of the means for which a valid rejection has been made should not be considered criminal.
The Expert Panel also calls for health care professionals to be trained in the task of respecting the removal of resources at the end of their lives, without having to fear criminal prosecution.
The panel stated that governments, health care institutions and doctors worked together on pain relief to provide the best pain relief remedies, and beyond cancer cases.
Last but not least, the panel calls for at least consideration of pain relief or life-saving measures already widely used in the Canadian institutions for health care, as they did not serve as much as euthanasia to reduce physical pain and to address it with the same procedures.
Subject matter of other experts
Some experts in the field of health care have already made reservations regarding the conclusions of the expert report of the Royal Canadian Society.
RA Pierre Deschamps, a health law specialist, referred to the attitude of the report-signing experts as "extreme" among other things, since it does not limit the practice of euthanasia in the case of patients in the final phase.
"This opens the door to a situation where everyone who is tired of living and over 18 years of age is asking another person to help him in his suicide," said RA Deschamps, who had seen a summary of the report yesterday.
RA Deschamps also stressed that the authors of the report seemed to place the individual's own responsibility for all the other values involved in the social activity of society.
But now, he says, there would be "guidelines and obligations in a society".
Margaret Somerville, Health Law Specialist, also expressed "a strong resistance" to the conclusions of the report, which she described as "pro-Euthanasia Manifest".
Margaret Somerville, herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, doubts in particular the reports on the non-prevention of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and accompanied suicide are legalized, such as the Netherlands and Oregon.
