Austria
Registration of a "Golden Budget Rule" in the Constitution
On Tuesday, the government of the Great Socialist/Christian-Democratic Coalition in Austria decided to include a "Golden Budget Rule" in the Constitution in order to reduce public deficits and also avoid any degradation by rating agencies in Austria's top bonus (AAA).
It was the Social-Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann who announced this decision at the end of the Council of Ministers, although the public debt of Austria is 74.6%, far above the 60% criterion laid down by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debt level of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's ability to pay hadn't fallen to AA+ at once, we would have to pay an additional three billion euros each year," argued Michael Spindelegger, Vice Chancellor and Christian-Democratic Minister of Foreign Affairs.
Austria also meets a demand from the Brussels Eurozone Member States on 26 October: the Heads of State or Government would have called for the introduction of a reduction in public deficits by the end of 2012, as well as a return to the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or through the adoption of an equivalent law.
The measure taken by the Austrian government is similar to the "German model", since Germany had been the first European country to include such a "rule" in the Constitution.
By 2017, the structural budget deficit should fall by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, while from 2017 the structural budget deficit of the state should not exceed the 0.35% of GDP limit, whereas the regional states as well as the municipalities should have balanced budgets.
The aim is to eliminate budgetary debt in the horizon of 2020/21 below the 60% criterion laid down by the Maastricht Agreement.
