Energy policy:
The facts should prevail over dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be addressed on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, this is certainly the energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to hold an election to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores the overall economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although 7 billion people are on this planet, demographic evolution is pushing for a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, a huge proportion of the world's population should not have to abandon a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources must be mitigated in order to continue to produce electricity, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, a topic that has disappeared from the environmental debate, in order to combat climate irregularities.
The accident of Fukushima does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany continues to be isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is neither the case in Belgium, which is subject to its decision to find a substitute source, nor in Switzerland, which is planning to build only nuclear power stations of the last generation.
By contrast, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name just a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, decided after Fukushima to join another unit in its park by re-establishing the Three Mile Island plant that was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Even though the German model, which is based on renewable energy sources, is sometimes set as a model, reality contradicts the discourse.
The Berlin election will result in an increase in electricity prices, an increase in energy dependence on imported gas, especially from Russia, and an increase in CO2 emissions from gas and coal plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will become apparent within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives rise to reflection.
Denmark is, on the one hand, the European table leader in wind energy, from which it refers to 30% of its electricity, on the other hand, the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, alternately used with wind energy; on the other hand, its CO2 emissions and electricity prices are 65% and 50% respectively higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the persistence of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill, unlike our French households.
Since energy prices in the globalised economy are a key factor in competitiveness and a stability path for industry on the national level, French companies have an advantage due to the best electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore lead to a strong increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements on the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys showed that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are just as willing to pay, as it shows resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Let us note that the energy policy of our country has enabled us to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a wealth of specialised small and medium-sized enterprises to the international markets and makes them the creators of countless jobs.
If France took the decision to withdraw from nuclear power, most of these SMEs would be victims, and the annual EUR 6 billion in exports of capital goods and nuclear energy would be reduced more and more.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed for operation over sixty years if the decline of his producer is pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energetic equation, one has to admit that there is just as little a miracle to the production of electricity as a devil's work.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy demonstrate the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a safety authority that carries out uncompromised and transparent controls in existing plants, such as at the construction site in Flamanville.
Their teams, who have made a name for themselves due to their professionalism, are just possessed by the safety concept.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious disturbances.
Only one, namely in Three Mile Island, entered under normal operating conditions; so it was without consequences for humans and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was evoked by reactor construction as well as inexcusable human failure.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters that caused the death of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw its lessons from this accident just as it did after the two previous accidents.
As a result of this approach and a cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR presents a draft that allows it to be resistant to such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among electric technicians to build a nuclear power plant, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF by allowing them to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and party manoeuvres to dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy led by Nicolas Sarkozy was criticised from many angles - overloading police, judicial and administrative bodies due to a number-based policy, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France itself had called itself.
Recently, the harassment of foreign students on the part of the public authorities had marked the weekly shows, the Minister of the Interior had occasionally announced (see Libération of 23 May) that France "needed no talent, masonry or waiters from abroad".
But this policy was rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right the sound of Jacques Chirac, who had declared in 1976 that "900.000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", on the left by Michel Rocard, who had stated in 1990 that France "could not absorb the whole poverty of the world".
The only difference is in the degree of large-scale mobility
The fear of the invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was divided in 2005 both from the right and from the left.
The two camps saw immigrants as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity to which immigrants are allowed.
In his programme, Francois Hollande confines itself to banalities which indicate that partnership development allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on the elections, but it is economically costly.
As economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recently published book that summarizes the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of the influx of immigrants on economic growth, wages and jobs in the countries of immigration.
Reducing immigration would undermine growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to replace the local workforce, in particular the low skilled, by exerting pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that immigrants are, in fact, much more complementary than local wage earners, since they are mainly employed in sectors which are unladen in the workplace.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors where local wage earners do not travel much, the more skilled among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not aligned with the labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulties working in a country where there is a lack of anesthetists, so this complementarity also results in a positive effect of immigration on wages and national labour market situations between locals and migrants.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants would result in a co-related, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas and economic growth introduced by immigrants is acceptable (how much immigrant immigrants are among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social systems, with an average of about 1% of the total budget in European countries.
For example, the World Labour Organisation estimates that a person moving to Germany at the age of 30 will contribute a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget over his lifetime on average.
At the start of his mandate, Nicolas Sarkozy wished to bring about the missing intersections "with the teeth".
However, these said teeth, which should deter immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
