Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian Gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with splendor and glory.
Over 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly under sea level last Tuesday under orchestral sound and fine-tasting buffet.
German chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte symbolically turned the tax of the valve that transports Russian gas into the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe by a first 1.224 km of pipeline connecting the St Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of the French total consumption - will be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already let the possibility of building a third line on your own track.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this huge building seems like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will enable direct gas supply to Germany, avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a little of their power: for them, it is becoming more difficult to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, was not afraid to compare the Nord-Stream pipeline with a "new German-Sowietian pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically too sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply through the support of this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of a confirmation of European energy, as the project has broken the gap between Western and Eastern Europe.
Russia has in barely five years completed its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, Western countries, which have strong gas consumption and whose gas reserves are tending.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," confirmed François Fillon at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the major gas contracts are also important from a political and economic point of view.
All this explains the broad smile of the numerous gasprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater line consists of steel with concrete coating to protect it from ship's anchors.
It rests on the seabed, about 200 m deep.
Minefields dating from the Second World War had to be removed during their construction.
"Some hundred mines had to be carefully removed or destroyed," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The line is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which has been interrupted by nothing over the entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project managers have distanced themselves from it, as Sweden was reluctant to see a Russian state society permanently on its coasts.
"In the case of a havary, we close the gas throughput in less than a minute," Jens Müller specified.
In the case of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
This case, however, is considered unlikely by the designers, as the swathes were estimated to be stable by one leak per 100,000 years.
The state monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured by both an underwater robot controlled for external observation from a seagoing vessel and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, half a meter in diameter, is introduced into the inside of the pipe and moved through the gas pressure.
After three complete days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on any deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to function for fifty years without having to undergo even the smallest repair.
Gas circulation is simply guaranteed by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
However, the management remains in Gazprom's hands, holding 51% of the shares.
In addition, the German companies E. ON and BASF are included (percentage 15.5%), as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (percent 9%).
These five companies have formed a corporate community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom has then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport company, on the basis of a renewable 20-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real transport gas quantity fails," Jens Müller specified.
The financing of the gas transmission system was secured 30% of shareholders as well as 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are willing to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline shows up on a sandy, pine-forested coastline at Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4,5 meter-high valves form the gas outlet spout.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is passed on to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been delivered with a million cubic metres of Russian gas per passing hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic metres per hour and 6 million in 2012.
